<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is GraphQL?", answer: "GraphQL is a query language for APIs that lets clients request exactly the data they need. Unlike REST APIs that return fixed data structures, GraphQL allows you to specify which fields to include in the response. You write a query describing the shape of the data you want, and the server returns data in that exact shape. It was developed by Facebook and open-sourced in 2015." },
  { question: "What is the difference between a query, mutation, and subscription?", answer: "A query is a read operation that fetches data without side effects. A mutation is a write operation that creates, updates, or deletes data. A subscription establishes a persistent connection for real-time updates when data changes on the server. Queries are analogous to GET requests, mutations to POST/PUT/DELETE, and subscriptions to WebSocket connections." },
  { question: "What are arguments in GraphQL?", answer: "Arguments are parameters passed to fields to filter, sort, or configure the returned data. For example, user(id: 123) passes the id argument to the user field to fetch a specific user. Arguments can be required or optional and support types like Int, String, Boolean, Float, ID, enums, and custom input types." },
  { question: "Can I nest fields in GraphQL?", answer: "Yes, nested fields are a core feature. If a field returns an object type, you must specify which sub-fields to include. For example, querying a user with an address field requires specifying address { street city zip }. This allows you to traverse relationships and get exactly the data structure you need in a single request." },
  { question: "How do I use the generated query?", answer: "Copy the generated query and send it as the query parameter in a POST request to your GraphQL endpoint. Most GraphQL APIs accept a JSON body with a query key. You can use tools like Postman, curl, or a GraphQL client library in your programming language. If your query uses variables, include a variables object in the request body." }
]) %>

